<div style=3D"float: right;padding-top:2pt"></div><h1 id=3D"hid1" class=3D"=
section">QR decomposition</h1>
<p class=3D"author">by <span itemprop=3D"author" itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D=
"https://schema.org/Person"><a class=3D"author" id=3D"article-author" href=
=3D"https://www.statlect.com/about/#author">Marco Taboga</a></span>, PhD</p=
>
<p>
   The QR decomposition (or QR factorization) allows us to express a
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/vectors-and-matrices=
">matrix</a> having linearly
   independent columns as the product of 1) a matrix Q having orthonormal c=
olumns
   and 2) an upper triangular matrix R.
</p>
<p>
   In order to fully understand how the QR decomposition is obtained, we sh=
ould
   be familiar with the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/Gram-Schmidt-process=
">Gram-Schmidt process</a>.
</p>



<p><img width=3D"29" height=3D"24" src=3D"data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgo=
AAAANSUhEUgAAAB0AAAAYCAIAAACJPGHrAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAA=
AJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABJSURBVEhLY/z//z8DDQATlKY2GGrmgsL3yJEjUB4Dg42ND=
ZBEFiEeQPRCwGj4QsBQS7+j6QECRtMDBIymBwgYTQ8QMLTMZWAAAEw6JxXCQPIuAAAAAElFTkSu=
QmCC" alt=3D"Table of Contents" style=3D"vertical-align:-12px;cursor:pointe=
r"></p> =20
<div class=3D"clps" id=3D"table-of-contents"><div class=3D"tableOfContents"=
>
<p><span class=3D"tocTitle">Table of contents</span></p>
<ol><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposit=
ion#hid2">Overview of the decomposition</a></p></li><li><p><a href=3D"https=
://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposition#hid3">A formal statemen=
t</a></p></li><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-=
decomposition#hid4">Uniqueness of the decomposition</a></p></li><li><p><a h=
ref=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposition#hid5">Pre-m=
ultiplication by the Q factor</a></p></li><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.sta=
tlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposition#hid6">Square matrices</a></p></li=
><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposition=
#hid7">Application to linear regression</a></p></li><li><p><a href=3D"https=
://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-decomposition#hid8">Solved exercises<=
/a></p><ol><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/QR-dec=
omposition#hid9">Exercise 1</a></p></li></ol></li></ol>
</div></div>


<h2 id=3D"hid2" class=3D"subsection">Overview of the decomposition</h2>
<p>
   Remember that the Gram-Schmidt process is a procedure used to transform =
a set
   of  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/linear-independen=
ce">linearly independent</a>
   vectors into a set of  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebr=
a/orthonormal-basis">orthonormal
   vectors</a> (i.e., a set of vectors that have unit norm and are orthogon=
al to
   each other).
</p>
<p>
   In the case of a
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$K	imes L$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3872px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   matrix
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"A" style=3D"background-position:0px -4455px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>,
   denote its columns by
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"76" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq1]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3240px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>.
   If these columns are linearly independent, they can be transformed into =
a set
   of orthonormal column vectors
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"78" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq2]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3155px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   by using the Gram-Schmidt process, which alternates normalization steps =
and
   projection steps:
</p>
<ol>
   <li>
      <p>
         we start with the
         normalization<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"=
130" height=3D"47" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH=
5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq3]" style=3D"background-po=
sition:0px -2533px;"></span>where
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"43" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq4]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3778px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>
         denotes the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/ve=
ctor-norm">norm</a> of
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"25" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$A_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4203px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we project
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"25" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$A_{=08ullet 2}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4182px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         on
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4116px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=
=3D"sp" width=3D"176" height=3D"35" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQ=
ABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq5]" style=
=3D"background-position:0px -1895px;"></span>where
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"64" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq6]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3630px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/inner-p=
roduct">inner product</a> between
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"25" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$A_{=08ullet 2}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4182px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         and
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4116px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         and
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=0Barepsilon _{2}$" style=3D"background-position=
:0px -4385px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is the residual of the projection, orthogonal to
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4116px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we normalize the
         residual:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"116"=
 height=3D"47" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAE=
AAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq7]" style=3D"background-positi=
on:0px -2770px;"></span>
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we project
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"25" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$A_{=08ullet 3}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4224px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         on
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4116px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         and
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 2}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4160px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=
=3D"sp" width=3D"278" height=3D"35" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQ=
ABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq8]" style=
=3D"background-position:0px -1px;"></span>where
         the residual
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=0Barepsilon _{3}$" style=3D"background-position=
:0px -4364px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is orthogonal to
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 1}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4116px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         and
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"26" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q_{=08ullet 2}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4138px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we keep on alternating normalization steps (where projection resid=
uals are
         divided by their norms) and projection steps (where
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"22" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$A_{=08ullet l}$" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -4295px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is projected on
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"87" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq9]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3095px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>)
         until we have produced a set of orthonormal vectors
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"78" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq10]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3180px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
      </p>
   </li>
</ol>
<p>
   Note that the residuals can be expressed in terms of normalized vectors
   as<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"101" height=3D"38=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq11]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2981=
px;"></span>for
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"75" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$l=3D1,ldots ,L$" style=3D"background-position:0px -330=
2px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>,
   where we have
   defined<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"75" height=
