<h2 id=3D"hid6" class=3D"subsection">Square matrices</h2>
<p>
   When the matrix
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"A" style=3D"background-position:0px -4455px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   being decomposed is a square
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"42" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$K	imes K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3848px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   matrix,
   then<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"68" height=3D"3=
8" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAA=
BAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq29]" style=3D"background-position:0px -351=
6px;"></span><br>where
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"14" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4406px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$R$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4503px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   are both square
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"42" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$K	imes K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3848px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   matrices.
</p>
<p>
   But a square matrix
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"14" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4406px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   having orthonormal columns is a unitary matrix.
</p>
<p>
   Therefore, the QR decomposition of a square matrix having linearly indep=
endent
   columns is the product of a unitary matrix and an upper triangular matri=
x with
   strictly positive entries.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid7" class=3D"subsection">Application to linear regression</h2>
<p>
   The QR method is often used to estimate
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/linear-r=
egression">linear
   regressions</a>.
</p>
<p>
   In a linear regression we have an
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"39" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$N	imes 1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3920px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   vector
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"10" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$y$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4576px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   of outputs and an
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"42" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$N	imes K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3824px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   matrix of inputs whose columns are assumed to be linearly independent. W=
e need
   to find the
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"39" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"Kx1" style=3D"background-position:0px -3896px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   coefficient vector
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=08eta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -4527px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   that minimizes the mean squared errors made by using the fitted
   values<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"66" height=3D=
"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAA=
AABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq55]" style=3D"background-position:0px -3=
592px;"></span>to
   predict the actual values
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"10" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$y$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4576px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   The well-known solution to this problem is the so-called
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/OLS-esti=
mator-properties">ordinary least
   squares</a> (OLS)
   estimator<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"125" heigh=
t=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAAL=
AAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq56]" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -2580px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   We can simplify the formula for the OLS estimator, avoid to invert a mat=
rix
   and thus reduce the computational burden (and the possible numerical
   instabilities) by computing the QR decomposition of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -4479px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"68" =
height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEA=
AAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq57]" style=3D"background-positi=
on:0px -3554px;"></span>where
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"14" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Q$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4406px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   is
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"42" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$N	imes K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3800px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$R$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4503px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   is
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"42" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$K	imes K$" style=3D"background-position:0px -3848px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   Then, the OLS estimator
   becomes<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"168" height=
=3D"144" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAAL=
AAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq58]" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -1978px;"></span>or<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"8=
1" height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5B=
AEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq59]" style=3D"background-pos=
ition:0px -3117px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   The latter way of writing the solution is more convenient: since
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$R$" style=3D"background-position:0px -4503px;vertical-=
align:-5px"></span>
   is upper triangular, we do not need to invert it, but we can use the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/matrix-algebra/row-echelon-form">ba=
ck-substitution algorithm</a> to
   find the solution
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=08eta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -4527px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid8" class=3D"subsection"><a id=3D"exercise"></a><a id=3D"Proble=
ms"></a>Solved exercises</h2>
<p>
   Below you can find some exercises with explained solutions.
</p>
<h3 id=3D"hid9" class=3D"subsubsection">Exercise 1</h3>
<p>
   Compute the QR decomposition
   of<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"167" height=3D"74=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
AAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq60]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2122=
px;"></span>
</p>

<div class=3D"bproof"><span class=3D"bproof">Solution</span></div>
<div id=3D"idns1" class=3D"clps">
<p>The norm of the first column of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"A" style=3D"background-position:0px -4455px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"276" height=3D"13=
8" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAA=
BAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq61]" style=3D"background-position:0px -291=
px;"></span>Thus,
   the first orthonormal vector
   is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"238" height=3D"82=
" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAAB=
